00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:05.980
Second order kinetics.

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:09.720
Of the form, and then
there are two kinds.

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:21.410
There's first order, rather,
second order, in one reactant

00:01:21.410 --> 00:01:26.900
of the form A goes
to products.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:32.700
And then you have first order
in two reactants first order

00:01:32.700 --> 00:01:35.980
in two reactants.

00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:44.850
So I'll have the form A plus
B goes of products.

00:01:44.850 --> 00:01:46.960
Where that's first order in A
and first order in B, and this

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:49.640
is second order in A. So you can
think of this as A plus A

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:53.210
goes to products if you want.

00:01:53.210 --> 00:01:56.070
And there's some rate
constant k,

00:01:56.070 --> 00:01:57.860
associated with this reaction.

00:01:57.860 --> 00:01:59.380
And we do the rate analysis.

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:02.330
We write the rate
of this process.

00:02:02.330 --> 00:02:03.580
Minus dA/dt.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:10.440
And for the purpose of writing
on the board, and you might

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:12.030
want to do this also in
your homework, when

00:02:12.030 --> 00:02:15.320
you're tired of writing.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:18.130
I'm going to skip
the brackets.

00:02:18.130 --> 00:02:23.040
The little brackets that we
usually put for concentration.

00:02:23.040 --> 00:02:24.780
I'm going to skip those, because
it's just too much

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:26.125
work to write them.

00:02:26.125 --> 00:02:30.510
And you can understand that A
is a concentration of A. So

00:02:30.510 --> 00:02:34.250
this is equal to k A squared.

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:39.490
Second order on A. And the units
for k, it's important to

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:43.280
keep track of your units, at the
end of the calculations,

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:46.030
often you want to make sure
your units work out.

00:02:46.030 --> 00:02:48.730
So the units for k are going
to be of this, A is

00:02:48.730 --> 00:02:50.400
in moles per liter.

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:53.600
The units for k, you're going
to have to be able to match

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:55.200
the units on this side here.

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:59.070
So the units for k are going to
be liters squared per mole

00:02:59.070 --> 00:03:04.960
squared per second.

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:06.830
To make the units match.

00:03:06.830 --> 00:03:11.140
Then you integrate this, on both
sides, from zero to t, or

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:18.630
from A0, the initial rate, to A.
Or from zero to t and this

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:22.180
doesn't go like this.

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:32.470
So integrate with A0 to A.
You've got dA over A squared,

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:35.520
you put all the A's on one side,
all the t's on the other

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:43.160
side, from zero to t dt with a
minus k on this side here.

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:50.420
And then you get your rate
equation, integrated rate

00:03:50.420 --> 00:03:52.630
equation for this.

00:03:52.630 --> 00:04:01.240
Which gives you one over A is
equal to kt plus one over A0.

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:03.600
So this gives you A as
a function of time.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:06.610
And this is a convenient way
to write it, because it's

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:07.410
linear in time.

00:04:07.410 --> 00:04:09.650
So you always try to get things
to be linear in time.

00:04:09.650 --> 00:04:15.360
Because then you can plot
them as a straight line.

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:20.460
Plot on this axis here you plot
one over A. on this axis

00:04:20.460 --> 00:04:25.650
here you plot t as a
function of time.

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:34.420
And then you get a straight
line where the slope is k.

00:04:34.420 --> 00:04:39.460
Gives you the rate, and the
intercept is one over A0.

00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:39.720
Yes.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:45.450
